We begin by extracting the key numbers from each statement:

1. Debt to Asset Ratio  
 • From the balance sheet, total liabilities are the sum of Accounts Payable and Taxes Payable:  
  Total Liabilities = 302,000.00 + 197,821.72 = 499,821.72  
 • Total Assets (end amount) = 14,890,758.71  
 • Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets = 499,821.72 / 14,890,758.71 ≈ 0.0336  
  Rounded to two decimal places, this is 0.03.

2. Gross Profit Margin  
 • From the income statement, Gross Profit = 2,272,433.90 and Total Revenue = 3,956,433.90.  
 • Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100 ≈ (2,272,433.90 / 3,956,433.90) × 100 ≈ 57.45%.

3. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
 • From the cash flow statement, the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -1,182,491.05.  
 • The total current liabilities (from the balance sheet) = 499,821.72.  
 • Operating Cash Flow Ratio = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities ≈ -1,182,491.05 / 499,821.72 ≈ -2.37.

Thus, the solution is:

  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.03",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "57.45%",
    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-2.37"
  }
}
